    summary: `"Exposure" by Wilfred Owen is one of the most powerful anti-war poems ever written, depicting the agonising experience of British soldiers enduring freezing winter conditions in the trenches of World War One. The poem was composed between late 1917 and early 1918, drawing directly on Owen's own experiences serving on the Western Front in France. Rather than focusing on the dramatic violence of battle, Owen turns his attention to the slow, insidious suffering caused by the weather — the bitter cold, the relentless wind, and the snow that gradually kills the soldiers as surely as any bullet or shell.

The poem opens with the soldiers huddled in their trenches at night, kept awake by the biting wind and the distant sounds of gunfire. Owen establishes immediately that the real enemy is not the opposing army but nature itself: "Our brains ache, in the merciless iced east winds that knive us." The men are trapped in a state of agonised waiting, unable to act, unable to retreat, simply enduring. The repeated refrain "But nothing happens" underscores the futility and monotony of trench warfare — the soldiers suffer immensely, yet their suffering achieves nothing and leads nowhere.

As the poem progresses, Owen moves through different stages of the night. Dawn arrives but brings no comfort — it is described as a "melancholy army" attacking the soldiers with its grey, cheerless light. The men begin to hallucinate and dream of home, imagining warm fires and closed doors, but even these dreams offer no real escape. Owen suggests that the doors of home are "closed" to them — they can never truly return to the innocent world they left behind. The war has changed them irrevocably.

In the later stanzas, the cold intensifies and the soldiers begin to freeze to death. Owen describes the snow with a disturbing tenderness, as if it is gently tucking the men in for an eternal sleep. The imagery shifts from suffering to a kind of numb acceptance. The soldiers' eyes become like ice, and they lose the ability to feel pain — a mercy that is also a death sentence. Owen draws a devastating parallel between the freezing soldiers and Christ's sacrifice, questioning what purpose their deaths serve.

The poem concludes with one of the most haunting endings in war poetry. The dead soldiers are discovered with their eyes frozen shut, their bodies covered in snow. The final repetition of "But nothing happens" drives home Owen's central argument: these men have died for nothing. Their sacrifice is meaningless, their suffering purposeless. The weather, not the enemy, has claimed them, and the war machine continues regardless. Owen forces the reader to confront the sheer waste of human life in war, not through scenes of dramatic combat, but through the quiet, relentless destruction of young men by cold and exposure.`,

    context: `Wilfred Owen (1893–1918) is widely regarded as the greatest poet of the First World War. Born in Oswestry, Shropshire, Owen was teaching English in France when war broke out in 1914. He enlisted in the Artists' Rifles in October 1915 and was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the Manchester Regiment in June 1916. His first significant combat experience came in January 1917 when he was posted to the Western Front in France. The horrors he witnessed — including being blown into the air by a trench mortar and spending days sheltering in a hole beside the remains of a fellow officer — led to his diagnosis with shell shock (now known as PTSD) in May 1917.

Owen was sent to Craiglockhart War Hospital in Edinburgh to recover, where he met the poet Siegfried Sassoon. This meeting was transformative: Sassoon encouraged Owen's writing and helped him develop his distinctive poetic voice. "Exposure" was drafted during late 1917 and revised in 1918, drawing on Owen's traumatic experiences during the particularly brutal winter of 1917 on the Western Front, where temperatures regularly dropped well below freezing and soldiers suffered from frostbite, trench foot, and hypothermia.

Owen returned to the front line in August 1918, driven by a sense of duty to his men and a desire to bear witness to their suffering. He was killed on 4th November 1918, just one week before the Armistice was signed. His mother received the telegram informing her of his death on 11th November — Armistice Day itself. Most of Owen's poems, including "Exposure," were published posthumously. The poem reflects Owen's determination to tell the truth about war, rejecting the patriotic propaganda that had encouraged young men to enlist. His famous preface states: "My subject is War, and the pity of War. The Poetry is in the pity."`,

