    languageAnalysis: `Armitage's language in "Remains" is deliberately colloquial, conversational, and understated — a choice that makes the poem's devastating content all the more powerful. The speaker uses the everyday language of a soldier recounting an anecdote: "On another occasion," "we got sent out," "legs it," "End of story." This register is authentic to the military context — soldiers do not typically use elevated literary language to describe their experiences — and it creates a surface of normality that makes the horror beneath all the more shocking.

The poem makes extensive use of military slang and colloquialisms. "Legs it" for running away, "tackle" for dealing with, "sent out" for deployed — these are the words of a working soldier, not a literary poet. This linguistic authenticity is crucial to the poem's impact: it establishes the speaker as a real, ordinary person, not a character in a drama. When the same ordinary voice describes "tossing" a dead man's intestines back into his body, the collision between the everyday tone and the horrific content creates a profound cognitive dissonance that is deeply unsettling.

Armitage employs the present tense throughout the poem's second half, even though the events being described occurred in the past. This temporal shift is one of the poem's most important technical features: it reflects the way traumatic memories remain vivid and present, refusing to fade into the past tense where they belong. "His bloody life in my bloody hands" and "he's here in my head when I close my eyes" are in the present because for the speaker, the dead man's death is not a past event but a current, ongoing reality. The shift from past to present tense enacts the very psychological process the poem describes.

The repetition of "probably armed, possibly not" at two key points in the poem creates a structural echo that mirrors the repetitive loops of PTSD. The first instance occurs during the description of the shooting; the second occurs when the speaker is trying to sleep. The phrase has migrated from its original context into the speaker's psychological interior, demonstrating how traumatic details break free from their narrative context and take on autonomous, intrusive life.

Armitage's use of enjambment is crucial to the poem's impact. Lines run on without pause, creating a flowing, almost breathless narrative that mimics the unstoppable quality of the speaker's memories. The lack of regular line endings or stanza breaks (the poem is written in loose, irregular stanzas) reflects the formlessness of the speaker's psychological experience — his thoughts and memories do not arrange themselves into neat patterns but spill uncontrollably across boundaries.`,

    structureAnalysis: `"Remains" is written in free verse with no regular metre or rhyme scheme, reflecting the conversational, spontaneous quality of the speaker's testimony. The poem reads like spoken language transcribed directly onto the page, with all the hesitations, corrections, and digressions of natural speech. This apparent formlessness is deliberate: Armitage wants the poem to feel authentic and unpolished, as if the speaker is talking directly to the reader rather than performing a literary composition.

The poem is divided into eight stanzas of varying length, most consisting of four lines (quatrains) but with significant variation. This near-regularity creates a visual impression of order that is constantly being disrupted — much like the speaker's attempts to maintain emotional control. The stanzas provide a framework, but the content repeatedly overflows its boundaries through enjambment, creating a tension between containment and release that mirrors the speaker's struggle to contain his traumatic memories.

The poem's most important structural feature is its pivot at the line "End of story, except not really." This divides the poem into two halves: the first describing the external event (the shooting), the second describing the internal aftermath (the psychological haunting). The structure thus mirrors the experience of PTSD: the traumatic event (which may be brief) and the long, seemingly endless aftermath (which may last years or decades). The second half of the poem is longer than the first, reflecting the way the psychological consequences of violence far outlast the violence itself.

The poem's use of enjambment across stanza breaks creates a sense of unstoppable momentum. Thoughts spill from one stanza to the next without pause, refusing to be contained by the visual structure of the poem. This technique is particularly effective in the poem's second half, where the intrusive memories flow unchecked across all boundaries — stanza breaks, line breaks, even the boundary between waking and sleeping life. The structure enacts the very loss of control that the speaker describes.

The absence of a concluding resolution is structurally significant. The poem does not end with recovery, acceptance, or even understanding — it simply stops, with the speaker still trapped in his psychological nightmare. This open-ended structure reflects the ongoing nature of PTSD and refuses to offer the reader the comfort of closure.`,

